#compdef reth-database-reader
# ============================================================================
# reth-database-reader - reth-indexer: read directly
#   from the reth Ethereum execution-client DB and
#   index decoded events into Postgres / BigQuery /
#   Parquet / CSV / an HTTP API (Rust, MIT)
#
# Author : Josh Stevens (joshstevens19)
# Upstream: https://github.com/joshstevens19/reth-indexer
# crates : reth-database-reader (binary:
#           reth-database-reader)
#
# `reth-database-reader` is the binary side of
# Stevens's reth-indexer project. It opens the reth
# Ethereum execution client's on-disk database
# directly (no HTTP/JSON-RPC round-trip), walks the
# block tree filtered by configurable ABI-decoded
# event signatures, and streams the decoded event
# rows into one or more output sinks:
#   - Postgres (via tokio-postgres, this file's
#     canonical-library hook)
#   - Google Cloud BigQuery (via bigquery rest API)
#   - Parquet files
#   - CSV files
#   - HTTP API endpoint (exposes query-able snapshot
#     of indexed data via warp)
#
# Operational positioning:
#   - Faster than EVM-RPC indexing (no JSON
#     serialization, direct MDBX reads)
#   - More flexible than block-explorer-API indexing
#     (decode any contract's events with just an ABI
#     JSON + config block)
#   - Designed for analytics / data-warehouse use
#     cases where the events need to land in a
#     queryable store, not for real-time mempool
#     monitoring
#
# Usage:
#   reth-database-reader
#   API=1 reth-database-reader            # serve
#                                           query API
#                                           only
#   CONFIG=./config.json reth-database-reader
#
# Configuration is via JSON file (default
# `./reth-indexer-config.json`) with sections for:
#   - reth_db_location
#   - postgres / bigquery / parquet / csv sink
#     configuration
#   - per-event-signature filter rules + ABI
#     definitions
#   - block-range bounds + reorg-handling settings
#
# Environment variables:
#   API                       - if set, run the
#                                query-API server
#                                only (skip indexing)
#   CONFIG                    - alternate config path
#                                (default
#                                ./reth-indexer-config.json)
#   RUST_LOG                  - env_logger filter
#                                (e.g. info, debug)
#
# The tokio-postgres lane is built on `tokio-postgres =
# "0.7.2"` (declared verbatim at upstream Cargo.toml
# HEAD as a direct dep, with `rust_decimal = { ...,
# features = ["db-tokio-postgres"] }` for numeric
# column round-tripping), the canonical Rust Postgres
# client by Steven Fackler (sfackler) - github.com/
# sfackler/rust-postgres, 3700+ stars on the
# rust-postgres umbrella.
#
# sfackler's rust-postgres umbrella covers:
#   - `postgres` (sync API, blocking I/O)
#   - `tokio-postgres` (async API, tokio runtime)
#   - `postgres-protocol` (low-level wire-protocol
#     codec; the canonical implementation of Postgres
#     protocol v3 in Rust)
#   - `postgres-types` (PostgreSQL <-> Rust value
#     conversions for the standard type set + macros
#     for custom types)
#   - `tokio-postgres-rustls` + `tokio-postgres-
#     native-tls` (TLS adapters)
#
# The rust-postgres umbrella implements PostgreSQL's
# frontend/backend protocol v3 byte-for-byte: simple
# + extended queries, prepared statements + bind
# parameters, COPY in/out streaming, NOTIFY/LISTEN
# pub/sub, transactions + savepoints, cancellation
# requests + SSL/GSSAPI/SCRAM-SHA-256 authentication.
# Fackler's umbrella has been the de-facto Rust
# Postgres client since 2015 - depended on by Diesel
# (the major Rust ORM), SeaORM, SQLx (which has its
# own protocol impl but cross-validates against
# rust-postgres), the Apache Datafusion Postgres
# table provider, and every Rust web framework with
# Postgres examples.
#
# Fackler is also a multi-axis canonical-Rust author:
#   - Axis 256 (Postgres, THIS AXIS):
#     sfackler/rust-postgres umbrella
#   - rust-openssl: the canonical Rust OpenSSL binding
#   - log: the de-facto Rust logging facade
#
# This makes Fackler one of the multi-axis canonical
# author cohort alongside:
#   - Andrew Gallant / BurntSushi (XXHash+TOML+
#     Snappy+regex+ripgrep+fst+xsv)
#   - Armin Ronacher / mitsuhiko (similar+redis-rs+
#     insta+minijinja+Flask+Jinja2)
#   - Vincent Prouillet / Keats (bcrypt+jsonwebtoken)
#   - Daniel Lemire (Roaring Bitmap across Rust + Go +
#     C + C++ + Java)
#   - Paul Miller / paulmillr (noble-ed25519 + noble-
#     curves + noble-hashes + noble-ciphers)
#
# reth-database-reader uses tokio-postgres in
# src/postgres.rs to:
#   - establish the pooled connection to the target
#     Postgres warehouse
#   - prepare per-event-type INSERT statements at
#     indexer-startup
#   - bind decoded event rows + execute in batched
#     transactions for throughput
#   - handle reorg-induced row deletes via
#     transactional rollback
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 256 :: Postgres protocol (frontend/backend
#              wire-protocol v3) client libraries
# Round 1466 :: Rust slot 1 of 4 :: OPENS Axis 256
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis
# (proposed):
#   Rust    : sfackler/rust-postgres      - the de-
#             umbrella (postgres /          facto Rust
#             tokio-postgres /              Postgres
#             postgres-protocol /           client
#             postgres-types)               umbrella;
#                                            Fackler's
#                                            multi-axis
#                                            canonical
#                                            position
#                                            (postgres +
#                                            rust-openssl +
#                                            log)
#   Go      : jackc/pgx                    - the de-facto
#                                            Go Postgres
#                                            driver by
#                                            Jack
#                                            Christensen;
#                                            implements
#                                            the protocol
#                                            directly +
#                                            implements
#                                            the
#                                            database/sql
#                                            interface
#                                            for stdlib
#                                            compat
#   TS/Node : brianc/node-postgres         - Brian
#             (npm `pg`)                     Carlson's
#                                            canonical
#                                            Node
#                                            Postgres
#                                            client;
#                                            actively
#                                            maintained
#                                            since 2010;
#                                            ~16M weekly
#                                            npm
#                                            downloads
#
# Postgres protocol is a clean spec-bound axis - the
# PostgreSQL frontend/backend protocol v3 document
# (https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/protocol.
# html) defines the wire format byte-for-byte. All
# three lanes implement protocol v3 byte-identically.
#
# Structural commentary on the canonical libraries:
#   - sfackler/rust-postgres (Rust): umbrella with
#     ~5 sibling crates split by sync/async + TLS
#     adapter + low-level codec separation; Fackler's
#     multi-axis canonical position
#   - jackc/pgx (Go): Jack Christensen's library;
#     unusual in that it directly implements the
#     protocol + the database/sql interface, letting
#     it sit in both worlds (high-perf direct-pgx
#     APIs OR stdlib database/sql APIs at slightly
#     lower throughput)
#   - brianc/node-postgres (Node): Brian Carlson's
#     `pg` package since 2010; foundational to the
#     Node Postgres ecosystem - pretty much every
#     ORM + query builder + connection pool either
#     uses pg or implements an alternative to it
#
# Cross-language interop at the wire format level - a
# Postgres protocol v3 frontend message stream
# produced by rust-postgres + pgx + node-postgres is
# byte-identical to PostgreSQL server's expected wire
# format.
#
# Axis 256 opens with the Rust slot at Steven
# Fackler's canonical rust-postgres umbrella.
# ============================================================================

_reth-database-reader() {
    # No clap CLI - config is environment-driven (API + CONFIG env vars)
    _arguments
}

_reth-database-reader "$@"
